19:["$","div",null,{"className":"prose prose-lg prose-headings:font-serif prose-headings:text-foreground prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-teal prose-a:decoration-teal/30 hover:prose-a:decoration-teal prose-img:rounded-2xl max-w-none","children":[["$","h1","h1-0",{"children":"How to Build an Offline AI Assistant Using LM Studio"}],"\n",["$","p","p-0",{"children":"In an era where data privacy is paramount, relying entirely on cloud-based AI models isn't always the best solution. Running Large Language Models (LLMs) locally ensures that your data never leaves your machine, while also providing zero-latency responses once the model is loaded."}],"\n",["$","p","p-1",{"children":["Today, we're building a fully functional offline AI assistant using ",["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"LM Studio"}],"."]}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-0",{"children":"The Architecture of Local AI"}],"\n",["$","p","p-2",{"children":"Before we dive into the setup, it's important to understand how local AI works. Unlike API-based solutions (like OpenAI's GPT-4 or Google's Gemini), local models require computational power directly from your CPU and GPU. The more VRAM your GPU has, the faster the model will generate tokens."}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-0",{"children":"What is LM Studio?"}],"\n",["$","p","p-3",{"children":"LM Studio is an incredibly user-friendly desktop application that allows you to discover, download, and run local LLMs. It handles the complexities of hardware acceleration (like using Apple Metal, NVIDIA CUDA, or AMD ROCm) seamlessly in the background."}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-1",{"children":"Step-by-Step Setup"}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-1",{"children":"Step 1: Download and Installation"}],"\n",["$","p","p-4",{"children":["Head over to the ",["$","a","a-0",{"href":"https://lmstudio.ai/","children":"LM Studio website"}]," and download the client for your respective OS (Windows, macOS, or Linux)."]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-2",{"children":"Step 2: Selecting the Right Model"}],"\n",["$","p","p-5",{"children":"Once installed, use the search bar to find a model. For general assistance, I highly recommend:"}],"\n",["$","ul","ul-0",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Llama-3-8B-Instruct"}]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Phi-3-Mini-4K-Instruct"}]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","p","p-6",{"children":["$","em","em-0",{"children":["Tip: Look for the ",["$","code","code-0",{"className":"bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded-md font-mono text-sm text-teal before:content-none after:content-none","children":"Q4_K_M"}]," or ",["$","code","code-1",{"className":"bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded-md font-mono text-sm text-teal before:content-none after:content-none","children":"Q5_K_M"}]," quantization tags. These represent quantized (compressed) models that balance speed and accuracy, allowing them to run on standard consumer hardware."]}]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-3",{"children":"Step 3: Configuring the Local Server"}],"\n",["$","p","p-7",{"children":"LM Studio isn't just a chat interface; it can act as a local API server replacing cloud calls."}],"\n",["$","ol","ol-0",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":["Navigate to the ",["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Local Server"}]," tab on the left sidebar."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":["Click ",["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Start Server"}],"."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"children":["Note the port (usually ",["$","code","code-0",{"className":"bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded-md font-mono text-sm text-teal before:content-none after:content-none","children":"1234"}],")."]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-2",{"children":"Integrating the Local API in Next.js"}],"\n",["$","p","p-8",{"children":"Now that our local AI is running, let's create a simple Next.js client to communicate with it."}],"\n","$L1c","\n","$L1d","\n","$L1e"]}]
